<br>
Ehh, tens of millions is an exaggeration.  It was more like 3 or 4.  Regardless, it meant nothing, really.  Most of them didn't even know why they were there.  Again, I'd ask you to check out Kannt's link (it's just one example) regarding the &quot;knowledge base&quot; of the peace demonstrators.  I mean, anybody could get a few million half-wits around the world to do anything, if the cause was one that they'd be willing to rally to.  The causes of rebellion in here in the US and anti-Americanism abroad just happen to be popular ones.<br>
<br>
Let's look at it in perspective.  And we'll put aside the fact that they were for the most part completely clueless and just work with numbers.  And this is by no means scientific...<br>
<br>
There are approximately six billion people in the world.  Assuming that approximately 3.5 million of them marched on February 17th (think that was the day), that comes out to a whopping .058% of the world's population.  Wow!<br>
<br>
Ok, well let's be fair about this.  Let's say that each one of those 3.5 million represented, oh I dunno, one hundred unheard voices (and I think that's being generous).  That would mean that in reality some 350 million people feel the same way.<br>
<br>
That bumps the number up to roughly 5.8% of the world's population.  Is that your overwhelming dissent?<br>
<br>
You can argue with my numbers, certainly.  Like I said, it's by no means scientific.  My point is that it was a relatively miniscule number of people that showed up to protest, most of whom didn't have a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>*clue*</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> what they were talking about or why they were really even there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Were those people also &quot;neo-Marxists&quot;? =)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yeah, as a matter of fact.  And worse.<br>
<br>
A very good article about who sponsored the &quot;peace rallies&quot; here in the US and the UK can be found <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.usainreview.com/2_17_Anti_War_Protests.htm" target="top">here.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->  This comes from USA today, so it's not exactly an un-reputable source.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You have more and more trouble to hide your arrogance, and the fact that any other opinion makes you going &quot;epilleptic&quot;.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Don't confuse the fact that I know I'm right with the idea that I am arrogant.  I'd say it's more due to the fact that you're wrong than that you have a differing opinion.  Opinions I can deal with.  Unwillingness to apply logic to your opinions makes me mad, I'll admit.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How is that, because a bunch of countries do not support your country policy that you would boycot its products?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
First of all, I just don't buy into the notion that &quot;a bunch of countries do not support our policy&quot;.  France is the only real concern when it comes to opposition because they have veto power in the UN (not that it really matters much).  Belgium does not, Germany does not.  Russia and China will balk at any US initiatives because, well, that's just what they do.  They will go along in the end, with the worst case scenario being that they choose to abstain (which I personally do not think likely).  <br>
<br>
I just don't see the huge amount of dissent that you claim exists among other countries.  Sure, the media hypes what little there is...it makes great television, doesn't it?  Kinda like a &quot;David vs. Goliath&quot; story. But when you come right down to it, it's really just three countries, two of which don't count (no veto power).<br>
<br>
In regards to a boycott...<br>
Think of it as the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>other</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> side's form of protest.  We are allowed to do that too, aren't we?  Or is that a right reserved for the far left?<br>
<br>
Just like the people that marched earlier this month, the rest of us have ways of making our voices and our opinions heard.  Just so happens that boycott is a means of making those opinions felt at the same time.  If you ask me, it's a whole lot more effective than running around in the street singing &quot;koom-by-ah&quot;.<br>
<br>
Anyway, who's to say it will ever happen?  I'm just saying that it is a real possibility right now.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You are certainly aware of what will happen the day Japan and China take back their investments into USA to put it somewhere else, arent you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sure I am.  But as it happens, Japan is a very close ally, and China is doing all it can to become a major player on the world stage.  In other words, neither of these things are going to happen.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>you need us exactly the same way, which you seem to have trouble understanding.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, see, you're only partially correct.  Think of it this way...<br>
<br>
What would happen to France without the United States?  Conversely, what would happen to the United States without France?<br>
<br>
You see my point?  Ok, good.<br>
